author: @ipsgpyc
text: IN operator is a shorthand for multiple OR Statements.¬†  In the example Alex writes, SELECT * FROM EmployeeDemographics WHERE FirstName = ‚ÄúJim‚Äù AND FirstName=‚ÄúMichael‚Äù; then explains we can use IN instead of multiple AND Operators.  In above mentioned query, we are looking for someone with both Jim and Michael as their firstname.  Instead, we are looking for rows where FirstName is either Jim or Michael.  We can achieve this by simply using OR operator instead of AND operator.  SELECT * FROM EmployeeDemographics WHERE FirstName = ‚ÄúJim‚Äù OR FirstName=‚ÄúMichael‚Äù;  Rather than writing multiple OR operator like above, we can use IN. SELECT * FROM EmployeeDemographics WHERE FirstName IN (‚ÄúJim‚Äù , ‚ÄúMichael‚Äù)
